The paper deals with lower bounds on the number of electrical transformations required to reduce a plane graph, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of homotopy moves and planar embeddings suggests connections to algebraic topology (cs.AT) and graph theory (cs.DM). The concept of defect in the medial graph relates to graph drawing and graph theory (cs.GT). Finally, the study of planar electrical transformations has applications in circuit design and optimization, which falls under the sub-category of computational engineering, finance, and science (cs.SI).
